class Solution:
    def minChanges(self, n: int, k: int) -> int:
        if n == k:
            return 0
        if (n & k) != k:
            return -1
        return bin(n ^ k).count('1')
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The key insight is that any bit set in k must already be set in n (otherwise impossible). The required flips are exactly the 1-bits in n that are 0 in k, counted via XOR and popcount.

